<p><b>Colitis</b> (<a href="/wiki/Plural" title="Plural">pl.</a> colitides) refers to an <a href="/wiki/Inflammation" title="Inflammation">inflammation</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Colon_(anatomy)" title="Colon (anatomy)" class="mw-redirect">colon</a>.</p>
<p>Colitis may be <a href="/wiki/Acute_(medicine)" title="Acute (medicine)">acute</a> and self-limited or <a href="/wiki/Chronic_(medical)" title="Chronic (medical)" class="mw-redirect">chronic</a>, i.e. persistent, and broadly fits into the category of <a href="/wiki/Digestive_diseases" title="Digestive diseases" class="mw-redirect">digestive diseases</a>.</p>
<p>In a medical context, the label <i>colitis</i> (without qualification) is used if:</p>
<ul>
<li>The cause of the inflammation in the colon is undetermined; for example, <i>colitis</i> may be applied to <i><a href="/wiki/Crohn%27s_disease" title="Crohn's disease">Crohn's disease</a></i> at a time when the <a href="/wiki/Diagnosis" title="Diagnosis">diagnosis</a> is unknown, or</li>
<li>The context is clear; for example, an individual with <a href="/wiki/Ulcerative_colitis" title="Ulcerative colitis">ulcerative colitis</a> is talking about their disease with a physician who knows the <a href="/wiki/Diagnosis" title="Diagnosis">diagnosis</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p></p>
